# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apple-pie
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apple-pie/14th-century] The **14th century** lasted from 1 January 1301 (represented by the Roman numerals MCCCI) to 31 December 1400 (MCD).
[src:apple-pie/14th-century] It is estimated that the century witnessed the death of more than 45 million lives from political and natural disasters in both Europe and the Mongol Empire.
[src:apple-pie/14th-century] West Africa experienced economic growth and prosperity.
[src:apple-pie/14th-century] This period is considered the height of chivalry and marks the beginning of strong separate identities for both England and France as well as the foundation of the Italian Renaissance and the Ottoman Empire.
[src:apple-pie/14th-century] In Asia, Tamerlane (Timur), established the Timurid Empire, history's third largest empire to have been ever established by a single conqueror.
[src:apple-pie/14th-century] Scholars estimate that Timur's military campaigns caused the deaths of 17 million people, amounting to about 5% of the world population at the time.
[src:apple-pie/14th-century] Synchronously, the Timurid Renaissance emerged.
[src:apple-pie/14th-century] In the Arab world, historian and political scientist Ibn Khaldun and explorer Ibn Battuta made significant contributions.
[src:apple-pie/14th-century] In India, the Bengal Sultanate separated from the Delhi Sultanate, a major trading nation in the world.
[src:apple-pie/14th-century] The sultanate was described by the Europeans as the richest country to trade with.
[src:apple-pie/14th-century] The Mongol court was driven out of China and retreated to Mongolia, the Ilkhanate collapsed, the Chaghatayid dissolved and broke into two parts, and the Golden Horde lost its position as a great power in Eastern Europe.
[src:apple-pie/14th-century] In Africa, the wealthy Mali Empire, a huge producer of gold, reached its territorial and economic height under the reign of Mansa Musa I of Mali, the wealthiest individual of medieval times, and perhaps the wealthiest ever.
[src:apple-pie/14th-century] In the Americas, the Mexica founded the city of Tenochtitlan, while the Mississippian mound city of Cahokia was abandoned.
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] The **17th century** lasted from January 1, 1601 (represented by the Roman numerals MDCI), to December 31, 1700 (MDCC).
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] From the mid-17th century, European politics were increasingly dominated by the Kingdom of France of Louis XIV, where royal power was solidified domestically in the civil war of the Fronde.
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] The semi-feudal territorial French nobility was weakened and subjugated to the power of an absolute monarchy through the reinvention of the Palace of Versailles from a hunting lodge to a gilded prison, in which a greatly expanded royal court could be more easily kept under surveillance.
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] With domestic peace assured, Louis XIV caused the borders of France to be expanded.
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] It was during this century that the English monarch became increasingly involved in conflicts with the Parliament, which would culminate in the English civil war and an end to the dominance of the English monarchy.
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] It was also a period of development of culture in general (especially theater, music, visual arts and philosophy).
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] Some of the greatest inventions took place in this century.
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] It was during this period that the European colonization of the Americas began in earnest, including the exploitation of the silver deposits, which resulted in bouts of inflation as wealth was drawn into Europe.
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] Also during this period, there would be a more intense European presence in Southeast Asia and East Asia (such as the colonization of Taiwan).
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] These foreign elements would contribute to a revolution in Ayutthaya.
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] The Mataram Sultanate and the Aceh Sultanate would be the major powers of the region, especially during the first half of the century.
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] In the Islamic world, the gunpowder empires – the Ottoman, Safavid, and Mughal – grew in strength as well.
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] The southern half of India would see the decline of the Deccan Sultanates and extinction of the Vijayanagara Empire.
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] The Dutch would colonize Ceylon and endure hostilities with Kandy.
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] The end of the 17th century saw the first major surrender of Ottoman territory in Europe when the Treaty of Karlowitz ceded most of Hungary to the Habsburgs in 1699.
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] In Japan, Tokugawa Ieyasu established the Tokugawa shogunate at the beginning of the century, beginning the Edo period; the isolationist Sakoku policy began in the 1630s and lasted until the 19th century.
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] In China, the collapsing Ming dynasty was challenged by a series of conquests led by the Manchu warlord Nurhaci, which were consolidated by his son Hong Taiji and finally consummated by his grandson, the Shunzhi Emperor, founder of the Qing dynasty.
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] Qing China spent decades of this century with economic problems (results of civil wars between the Qing and former Ming dynasty loyalists), only recovering well at the end of the century.
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] The greatest military conflicts of the century were the Thirty Years' War, Dutch–Portuguese War, the Great Turkish War, the Nine Years' War, Mughal–Safavid Wars, and the Qing annexation of the Ming.
[src:apple-pie/17th-century] Major changes in philosophy and science take place, often characterized as the Scientific Revolution.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The **6abc Dunkin' Thanksgiving Day Parade** is an annual Thanksgiving Day parade held in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] It is currently sponsored and broadcast by ABC owned-and-operated television station WPVI-TV, through a co-sponsorship agreement with restaurant chain Dunkin'.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] It is currently the oldest Thanksgiving parade in the United States, having been held through the Great Depression and World War II, and was created by Gimbels department store in 1920.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Gimbels sponsored the parade until the store's bankruptcy and closure in 1986.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The annual Philadelphia Thanksgiving Day Parade began in 1920.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] It is the longest continuously held Thanksgiving day parade in the country.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Like other parades of its type, it features balloons, floats, high school marching bands, and celebrities.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Gimbels department store sponsored the 1920 parade as the Gimbels Thanksgiving Day Parade; it continued annually despite World War II.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Ellis Gimbel, one of the founders of Gimbels Department Stores, wanted his toy land to be the destination of holiday shoppers everywhere.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] He had more than 50 store employees dressed in costume and sent to walk in their first Thanksgiving Day parade.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The parade featured floats as marchers paraded down Market Street, with the parade's finale featuring Santa Claus arriving at the eighth-floor toy department at Gimbels, where he climbed the ladder of a Philadelphia Fire Department ladder truck.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Gimbels emulated other holiday parades already in existence.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The Santa Claus Parade in Peoria, Illinois, is held on the day after Thanksgiving and is the oldest, continuously held holiday parade in the country since 1887, under the sponsorship of Frederick Block and the Schipper & Block, later renamed Block & Kuhl Department Store.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Block's example led to the founding of similar parades in other cities.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] When Batus Inc., which then owned Gimbels, was unable to find a buyer for the store in 1986, the Gimbels' chain was liquidated, leaving the fate of the country's oldest parade uncertain.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Boscov's, a family-owned department store based in Reading, Pennsylvania, and WPVI (also known as 6abc), the ABC owned and operated station in Philadelphia, replaced Gimbels as sponsorships of the parade.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] They renamed the event as the 6abc Boscov's Thanksgiving Day Parade.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In 2004, the parade celebrated its 85th anniversary with new balloons and floats.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] An opening number paid tribute to the celebrities who had participated during its history.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In 2005, it featured the most celebrities in history, as well as eight new balloons, also the most in its history.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In 2007, the parade presented the first parade float with a built-in ice rink.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Disney's *High School Musical: The Ice Tour* utilized the rink.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In August 2008, Boscov's Department Stores filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection and planned to close several stores, due to financial problems from the widespread recession.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] They withdrew their sponsorship of the parade.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Swedish furniture manufacturer IKEA, which has a store and its North American home office in nearby Conshohocken, Pennsylvania, replaced Boscov's as parade co-sponsor from that year until 2010.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In June 2011, Dunkin' Donuts announced that they would sponsor the parade.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In addition to balloons and marching bands, the show features ABC stars, actors from stage and screen, Disney characters, and local personalities, including members of the Action News team.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In 2020, due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the parade was held as a television-only event.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The *6abc Dunkin' Thanksgiving Celebration* featured modifications similar to those made by the Macy's and America's Thanksgiving Parades.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The parade returned to its traditional format in 2021.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Since 1966, the parade has been broadcast on WPVI, as well as simulcast on other television stations throughout the United States.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Viewers could also watch the telecast on the station's website, 6abc.com, ABC News Live, Disney+ and Hulu, and since 2023, the parade has been aired internationally via the YouTube page of ABC News.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Jim O'Brien was the program's first host; Dave Roberts became a perennial host upon joining the station in 1978.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] After the sudden death of O'Brien in 1983, WPVI's Lisa Thomas-Laury joined as Roberts's co-host.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Together, Roberts and Thomas-Laury hosted the parade for nearly 20 years.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] When Thomas-Laury began to experience health problems in 2002, WPVI weather anchor Cecily Tynan replaced her.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] 2006 marked the program's first high-definition telecast.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Since her return to WPVI, Thomas-Laury helped host the finale in 2006 and 2007.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In 2009, the station announced that Roberts would retire from broadcasting on December 11 of that year.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Thomas-Laury made a special appearance in 2009, to celebrate Roberts's years as host.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Thomas-Laury (who would subsequently retire from broadcasting in 2016) and Roberts both made a special appearance in the broadcast booth during the centennial edition of the parade in 2019.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The current hosting team is Tynan and WPVI news anchor Rick Williams, who replaced Roberts.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Since 2024, the parade has simulcastly streamed nationally on ABC News Live, Disney+, and Hulu.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] WPVI also broadcasts annual live coverage of Philadelphia's Pulaski, Columbus, and Puerto Rican parades.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Balloons have been created to represent a wide variety of characters from popular children's books, including folk tales, toys, comic books, animated movies and cartoons, television series (such as *Sesame Street*), films and other genres.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Increasingly over the years, the balloons have featured characters who have tie-in marketing of toys, games, and accessories.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In addition to the well-known balloons and floats, the parade also features live music and other performances.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] High-school marching bands from across the country participate, and the television broadcasts feature performances by famous singers and bands as well as appearances by local celebrities and actors from ABC shows.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Since 1997, the parade has also featured a tap routine called "FanTAPulous," with more than 450 dancers from the East Coast.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Other special guests include state and national beauty contest winners, cheerleaders of major sports teams, casts from musicals performing in Philadelphia, and Santa and Mrs.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In 2024, the Philadelphia Ghostbusters joined the parade line up for the first time.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] They were accompanied by members of the Delco Ghostbusters, Ghostbusters of New Jersey, and Diamond State Ghostbusters.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] For more than 25 years, WPVI-TV has partnered with the Boy Scouts of America Cradle of Liberty Council in their *Scouting For Food* program to collectively coordinate one of the most massive food drives in the nation.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Until 2006, it was called the *6abc/Boy Scouts Holiday Food Drive*.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In 2006, the Holiday Food Drive amassed 120,000 lbs of food, and for 2010 Boy Scouts troops' efforts led to the collection of over 40,000 pounds of food towards the cumulative total.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The food drive distributes paper bags to residents' homes and collection boxes at local stores in the region.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] A few weeks later, they are sent to help those in need at Thanksgiving and the end of year holidays.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The Boy Scouts also go to the parade route every year and collect food from spectators.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The parade and food drive sponsors are generally the same.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In June 2011, Dunkin' Donuts announced that they would also co-sponsor the food drive.
[src:apple-pie/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Proceeds of the food drive currently benefit Philabundance.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] At the time, many ingredients were scarcely obtainable, but the book was quickly recognised as serious, and within a few years it profoundly changed English cooking and eating habits.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Returning to postwar England, still with food rationing, after years living in the Mediterranean with its wealth of fresh ingredients, Elizabeth David found life grey and daunting.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The food was terrible: "There was flour and water soup seasoned solely with pepper; bread and gristle rissoles; dehydrated onions and carrots; corned beef toad in the hole.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Partly to earn some money, and partly from an "agonized craving for the sun", David began writing articles on Mediterranean cookery.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Her first efforts were published in 1949 in the British edition of *Harper's Bazaar*.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] From the outset, David refused to sell the copyright of her articles, and so she was able to collect and edit them for publication in book form.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Even before all the articles had been published, she had assembled them into a typescript volume and submitted it to a series of publishers, all of whom turned it down.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] One of them explained that a collection of unconnected recipes needed linking text.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] David took this advice, but, conscious of her inexperience as a writer, she kept her own prose short and quoted extensively from established authors whose views on the Mediterranean might carry more weight.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] In the published volume, the sections are linked by substantial extracts from works by writers including Norman Douglas, Lawrence Durrell, Gertrude Stein, D.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Lawrence, Osbert Sitwell, Compton Mackenzie, Arnold Bennett, Henry James and Théophile Gautier.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] She submitted the revised typescript to John Lehmann, a publisher more associated with poetry than cookery, but he accepted it, agreeing to an advance payment of £100.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] *A Book of Mediterranean Food* was published in 1950.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Lehmann had suggested it be named "The Blue Train Cookery Book", since he supposed that the romance of Mediterranean countries was to be found in the exciting train journeys to reach them.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The book appeared when food rationing imposed during the Second World War remained fully in force in Britain.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The historian of food Panikos Panayi argues that with *A Book of Mediterranean Food*, David profoundly changed English cooking.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Lehmann commissioned a coloured dust-jacket painting and black and white internal illustrations from his friend the artist John Minton.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Writers including Cyril Ray and John Arlott commented that Minton's drawings added to the attractions of the book.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] David, a woman of strong opinions, thought good illustration important.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Minton provided 15 decorations to give a feeling of the Mediterranean, rather than simple illustrations of dishes from David's recipes.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] For example, his port scene shows a sailor drinking and conversing with a young woman beside a table laden with food; in the background is a street restaurant and boats in a harbour.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Although David did not like Minton's black and white drawings, she described his jacket design as "stunning".
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The chapters cover in turn: soups; eggs and luncheon dishes; fish; meat; substantial dishes; poultry and game; vegetables; cold food and salads; sweets; jams, chutneys and preserves; and sauces.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The soup chapter sets the pattern for the book, with short, simple recipes, such as soup of haricot beans – two brief paragraphs – interspersed with long, complex ones like that for Mediterranean fish soup, which covers three pages.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The eggs and luncheon dish section likewise balances the concise and simple such as *ratatouille aux oeufs* against the detailed and discursive three-page consideration of omelettes.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The meat section begins with recipes for veal, generally unfamiliar at English tables in 1950.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] David also gives recipes for kid and boar.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Mutton, by contrast, was more often served then than in more recent decades, and David gives four recipes for it, one of them disguising the flavour to taste like venison by long marinating and highly seasoned saucing.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The "substantial dishes" chapter discusses and illustrates the merits of risotto and paella, and deals with polenta and spaghetti – both less familiar in Britain then than now – and goes on to describe cassoulet.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The next chapter, on poultry and game, begins with recipes for cooking chicken and duck, and goes on to partridge – both *à la provençale* and in Greek style – quail and pigeons, concluding with snipe cooked *en papillote* with mushrooms.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The Mediterranean theme of the book is emphasised in the section on vegetables, in which there are five aubergine recipes and only one potato dish (*pommes Anna*).
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Dishes from Greece and North Africa are included along with typical southern French standards such as *tomates provençales*.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The occasional non-Mediterranean dish is included, including *cèpes à la bordelaise* fried in olive oil with parsley and garlic.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The cold food and salads chapter gives instructions for three dishes of cold chicken, several traditional pâtés and terrines, and another non-Mediterranean recipe, the traditional Easter dish from Burgundy, *jambon persillé de Bourgogne*.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] David adds to this section suggestions for hors d'oeuvres, including Greek dishes then unfamiliar in Britain including dolmádes and taramá, as well as traditional French recipes such as *sardines marinées à la niçoise*.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] In the section on sweets, David comments that throughout the Mediterranean countries, the more complicated sweets are very often bought from pâtisseries; the few recipes she gives are for simple, traditional sweets made at home, such as *torrijas* (also called *pain perdu*) and cold orange soufflé.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The jams, chutneys and preserves section includes preserved melon alongside more familiar fruits such as pears and plums.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] In the final chapter, on sauces, David includes classics like béchamel, béarnaise, hollandaise and mayonnaise (which, she advises, "stir steadily but not like a maniac").
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] To these she adds Turkish, Greek, Italian and Egyptian sauces, the majority of them intended to go with Mediterranean fish dishes.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Rachel Cooke, writing in *The Guardian*, quotes the chef Simon Hopkinson, who knew David in the 1980s, as believing that David's "powerful effect .. on British palates .. was as much a question of timing as anything else".
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Melanie McDonagh, writing in *The Telegraph*, states that with *A Book of Mediterranean Food*, David "introduced the Brits to the cooking of Greece, Italy and Provence in 1950 after her return from Greece, via Egypt and India".
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] She comments that the cookery writer Jane Grigson, a "devotee", said "Basil was no more than the name of bachelor uncles, courgette was printed in italics as an alien word, and few of us knew how to eat spaghetti ...
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Dissenting from the general acclaim, Tom Norrington-Davies, also writing in *The Telegraph*, argues that the book "reached only a very small section of the population", but at once qualifies this, stating that these readers were "undergoing a dramatic upheaval.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Educated, moderately wealthy women suddenly found themselves in their kitchens without servants".
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] He cites Jane Grigson's observation, introducing a collection of David's writing, that "Elizabeth didn't so much restore [middle-class women's] confidence in cooking as invent it".
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Joe Moran, writing in the *Financial Times*, describes the genesis of the book as a "defining moment".
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] It was when, "stranded by a blizzard" in a hotel in Ross-on-Wye whose restaurant served meals so dismal that they seemed to her to be "produced with a kind of bleak triumph which amounted almost to a hatred of humanity and humanity’s needs", David felt her famous "agonised craving for the sun".
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Furious at the joyless food, she started to draft the "sensuous descriptions" of Mediterranean food that led to *A Book of Mediterranean Food*.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Marian Burros, writing in *The New York Times*, comments that David first showed "her importance" with the book.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] "The ration-weary English could barely buy enough to eat but they were enchanted by her descriptions of meals that included eggs, butter, seafood, tomatoes, olives, apricots, ingredients that were difficult, or impossible, to obtain.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Foods that are taken for granted today in England – garlic, olive oil, Parmigiano Reggiano – were unknown and generally viewed with suspicion before Mrs.
[src:apple-pie/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The book has appeared in the following editions since 1950, including translations into Danish and Chinese.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Lucy encourages Charlie Brown to try and kick her football to honor the tradition of Thanksgiving football, then as usual pulls the ball away just before Charlie Brown reaches it and tells him that some traditions fade away.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Charlie Brown, Snoopy, Woodstock and Linus then prepare a feast of toast, pan-fried popcorn, pretzel sticks, jelly beans and sundaes.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Once the friends arrive, Linus says a grace based on the First Thanksgiving and Snoopy deals the plates like a casino dealer.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] An enraged Peppermint Patty rejects the meal for not including traditional foods.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Marcie reminds Peppermint Patty that she invited herself to the meal.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Peppermint Patty humbly asks Marcie to apologize to Charlie Brown on her behalf (unintentionally paralleling *The Courtship of Miles Standish*).
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Marcie reluctantly agrees, but Peppermint Patty soon follows and apologizes directly.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Charlie Brown calls his grandmother to explain why his family is late to dinner; she invites all his friends to join them.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] On the drive over, they sing "Over the River and Through the Wood"; Charlie Brown remarks the one thing wrong with a song about "grandmother's house:" his lives in a condominium.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Back at Snoopy's doghouse, he and Woodstock partake in a traditional meal among themselves.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] This is the last TV special that uses the same cast from *Snoopy Come Home*, *You're Not Elected, Charlie Brown*, and *There's No Time for Love, Charlie Brown*.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] In the next television special, Kohn, DeFaria, and Momberger would be succeeded in their respective roles by Melanie Kohn (Robin's younger sister), Donna Forman, and Lynn Mortensen, respectively.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The special first aired on CBS on Tuesday, November 20, 1973, two days before Thanksgiving.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] It placed third in the Nielsen ratings for the week, behind *All in the Family* and *Sanford & Son*.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The special continued to air every year on CBS (skipping 1982, 1983, and 1988) through Nov.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The Disney Channel and Nickelodeon returned the special for re-airing in the 1990s (in the latter channel's case, under the "You're on Nickelodeon, Charlie Brown" umbrella of productions) and then, in 2001, it moved, along with the rest of the *Peanuts* specials, to ABC.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] In contrast to CBS, ABC aired the special every year through 2019, on several days in the week leading up to Thanksgiving, and it regularly won its time slot.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] As the special runs slightly over a half-hour with commercials, ABC typically filled the remaining portion of the full hour with other *Peanuts* programming.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] From 2008 to 2019, the remaining time was filled by a slightly abridged edit of "The Mayflower Voyagers," the premiere episode of the 1988 miniseries *This Is America, Charlie Brown*.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Starting in 2020, the special (along with the rest of the *Peanuts* library) has exclusively aired on Apple TV+; under the terms of the agreement, Apple TV+ must provide a three-day window in November in which the special is available for free.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] On November 18, 2020, Apple announced they had reached an agreement to air the special on Sunday, November 22, 2020, the Sunday before Thanksgiving, commercial free on PBS and PBS Kids.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Apple renewed its exclusive streaming rights to the special in an agreement announced October 2, 2025, the 75th anniversary of the first published *Peanuts* comic strip.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The special is also broadcast in Canada, usually in early October in line with the Canadian observance of Thanksgiving.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The special is aired on Family Channel as of 2018, with the special aired on the day before Thanksgiving and on Thanksgiving Day, which takes place on the second Monday of October in Canada.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The music for *A Charlie Brown Thanksgiving* was composed by Vince Guaraldi and conducted/arranged by John Scott Trotter.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The score was recorded by the Vince Guaraldi Quintet on August 20, 22, September 4, and October 1 1973, at Wally Heider Studios, featuring Tom Harrell (trumpet), Chuck Bennett (trombone), Seward McCain (electric bass), and Mike Clark (drums).
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] On October 20, 2023, the complete original remastered recordings were officially released by Lee Mendelson Film Productions in honor of the special's 50th anniversary, presenting the full score and several previously unreleased tracks for the first time.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The special was released on RCA's SelectaVision CED format in 1982 as part of the *A Charlie Brown Festival Vol.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] It was released on VHS by Kartes Video Communications (later KVC Home Video) in 1987.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] It was released by Paramount Home Video on VHS on September 28, 1994 and was re-released in clamshell packaging on October 1, 1996.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] *A Charlie Brown Thanksgiving* was released on DVD by Paramount Home Entertainment on September 12, 2000.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] It was re-released by Warner Home Video in remastered form on October 7, 2008.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] It was released on a Blu-ray/DVD Combo Pack by Warner Home Video on October 5, 2010.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The special was released in a 40th anniversary deluxe edition DVD by Warner Home Video with the same features from previous editions on October 1, 2013.
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The deluxe edition DVD also features "The *Mayflower* Voyagers".
[src:apple-pie/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The special was released on Ultra HD Blu-ray on October 24, 2017.
[src:apple-pie/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] The book contains early recipes for plum (Christmas) pudding and suet pudding, and the first printed recipe for orange marmalade (without chunks).
[src:apple-pie/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] Mary Kettilby indicated her intended audience with the book's full title, *A Collection of above Three Hundred Receipts in Cookery, Physick and Surgery; For the Use of all Good Wives, Tender Mothers, and Careful Nurses*.
[src:apple-pie/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] The book was actually a collective effort: the preface states that "a Number of very Curious and Delicate House-wives Clubb'd to furnish out this Collection".
[src:apple-pie/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] The book contains an early recipe for suet pudding, and the first printed recipe for orange marmalade, though without the chunks typically used now.
[src:apple-pie/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] The book is divided into chapters for food and chapters for remedies.
[src:apple-pie/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] Apart from the Preface, there is no introduction of any sort: the recipes follow immediately after the chapter headings.
[src:apple-pie/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] The book is clearly divided into chapters of recipes for food and for remedies, but within the chapters there is no definite structure.
[src:apple-pie/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] For example, the first chapter begins with six recipes for soups, followed by recipes for collared beef, "French-Cutlets", collared mutton, stewed pigeons, broiled pigeons, dressed turbot, and then patties "for a Dish of Fish".
[src:apple-pie/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] While some logic may be discerned in this ordering, readers need to refer to the index to locate any particular dish.
[src:apple-pie/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] The recipes are given either as goals, as "To make Hogs-Puddings", or as titles, sometimes with descriptions, as "A very good Tansy".
[src:apple-pie/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] Quantities are given in whichever units are convenient, as "a Gallon of grated Bread", "three Pounds of Currants", or "nine Eggs".
[src:apple-pie/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] Often, quantities rely on the cook's judgement, as "as much Sugar as will make it very sweet".
[src:apple-pie/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] Temperatures and timings are given when necessary, as "a cool Oven: Half an Hour bakes it." There are no lists of ingredients.
[src:apple-pie/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] No additions were made to the 3rd, or 4th editions.
[src:apple-pie/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] Mary Ellen Snodgrass comments that the *Collection* was "for ordinary housewives", in "parallel to court cookbooks".
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] The book is divided into 15 chapters, forming a strict chronological sequence of periods such as "the Georgian age", from around 1150 to around 2000.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] The chapters describe the society of each time, often starting with the monarch and rich food and drink, and proceeding down to ordinary people and the common foods of the period.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] The narrative freely combine outlines of the historical context, descriptions of recipes, stories about significant figures, and personal anecdotes.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] For example, "The Medieval Larder" has an extensive section on the "medieval pig", leading into a description of Dickson Wright's own childhood memories of helping to kill her father's pigs and making black pudding, chitterlings and sausages, as well as having hams and bacon smoked.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Each chapter is opened with a monochrome illustration from its period, with a detailed caption.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] There are 32 pages of colour plates illustrating famous cookery writers such as Robert May and stages of English cuisine such as "The 1950s kitchen".
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] The book begins with a short introduction, in which Dickson Wright states that her "great passions" include food and history, so that she "always knew" she would come to write the book.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] She adds that another passion is field sports, "providing food and controlling pests and vermin", and that this runs like a "silver thread" through the book.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Dickson Wright begins around 1150 in the reign of King Henry II and Eleanor of Aquitaine, a time of relative peace and wealth.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] The diet she describes included rabbit, deer, carp farmed in ponds, eels, salmon, poultry, sheep, cattle, cheese, pigs, bread, onions, parsnips, carrots, and beans, washed down with wine and beer.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Spices such as pepper, cinnamon, and ginger were costly, and not used to try to make rotten meat acceptable; Dickson Wright suggests they more likely masked the salt used to preserve food.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] The 14th century *The Forme of Cury* often uses sugar alongside spices.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Recipes were complex; many dishes were served in pastry.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Each kind of meat was served with spices thought appropriate to it: for example, venison was eaten with sugar and cinnamon.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Dickson Wright describes in detail the diet and lifestyle of the Tudor Kings; under the influence of Catherine of Aragon, Henry VIII drank Spanish sherry, imported oranges, and planted salad gardens.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Enormous confections were made of marzipan.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Commoners too might eat sea and freshwater fish, or beef, though bacon, according to Andrew Boorde in 1542 was "good for carters and plowmen".
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] With the separation of the Church of England from the Church of Rome, religious fasting was reduced, and the fasting rules were relaxed in the time of Elizabeth I, so that eggs, cheese, and milk were allowed even on fast days.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Pastry developed from 'coffin' cases meant only to hold the food inside during cooking and serving; now pies and pasties of all kinds were available to travellers.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Milk and cream were used in desserts such as junkets and syllabubs.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] A treat might consist of buns made with eggs, raisins, and spices.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] In 1604, Elinor Fettiplace compiled a *Receipt Book*; she had married into an ancient aristocratic family – a Fettiplace fought at the Battle of Hastings in 1066; at least 20 people ate at her table every day.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] She lists several recipes for bitter Seville oranges.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Food is strongly seasonal; she pickles buds, vegetables, and fruits in season, and makes a spiced fruit cake for 100 people for a harvest or other feast.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] My Lord of Devonshire's Pudding is made of sliced white bread, dates, raisins, marrow or butter, cream, eggs, cinnamon, nutmeg, and sugar—a recipe that Dickson Wright specially likes.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] James I brought a new approach to English food in the Stuart era, introducing Scottish customs of boiling puddings in a cloth, cold-smoking fish, and baking biscuits such as shortbread.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Gervase Markham's 1615 *The English Huswife* calls for ingredients as varied as asparagus, capers, olives, lemons, and spinach.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Robert May's 1660 *The Accomplisht Cook* is based on his time in Paris, followed by being cook to the Grocer's Company and to the Star Chamber, providing elaborate feasts.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] He gives instructions for fattening up wild birds like godwits by force-feeding.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] He offers multiple recipes for sturgeon, at that time common in England's rivers.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] The East India Company increased foreign trade in the 17th century, bringing spices, pepper, cloves, mace, nutmeg, and tea from the East.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Meanwhile, bananas appeared from Bermuda.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] The Duke of York told the diarist Samuel Pepys that English seamen ate only "peas, pork, and boiled beef".
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] The adventurer Sir Kenelm Digby, alongside many activities at King James's court, in Italy, and in Spain, wrote a 1669 cookery book, *The Closet of the Eminently Learned Sir Kenelme Digbie Knight Opened*.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Many of the recipes are attributed to aristocratic connections; his *Pan Cotto* is "as the Cardinals use in Rome".
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] King James II's coronation banquet in 1685 presented some "1,500 dishes ranging from puffins to pistachio creams" in Westminster Hall.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Gin, at first imported from Holland to accompany William of Orange's Glorious Revolution of 1688, was soon widely distilled; the resultant heavy drinking led to the 1736 Gin Act.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] John Evelyn praised salads in his "pompous and verbose" 1699 book *Aceteria: A Discourse of Sallets*.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] The slave trade brought molasses, rum, and sugar, and black domestic servants to England.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Roasting and baking became less laborious with Georgian era innovations in fireplace and oven design, approaching a kitchen range; the poor prepared their pies and took them to the bakery to be cooked.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Josiah Wedgwood made fine earthenware dinner services for George III and the middle class.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Teapots diversified; Thomas Twining opened London's first tea-shop for ladies in 1717.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] In Dundee, James Keiller made marmalade from bitter Seville oranges.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Parson James Woodforde described sumptuous Georgian meals in his country parish.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] The 18th century, with a literate audience, saw the birth of English cookery books for the general public: some 300 appeared in the century.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Hannah Glasse's *The Art of Cookery Made Plain and Easy* came out in 1746 and went through 17 editions by 1800.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Dickson Wright comments that the text is clear and simple, and the recipes, "a delight to follow", always work.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Glasse introduces recipes for curry, and for ice cream.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] In the 19th century, Marie-Antoine Carême, who had worked for the Czar of Russia, introduced the modern system of separate soup, fish, meat, and dessert courses *à la russe*.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Alexis Soyer introduced elegant and complex French cuisine for the wealthy, and catered for the 1851 Great Exhibition, feeding 1000 people a day.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Charles Dickens's 1843 *A Christmas Carol* describes a recognisably modern Christmas dinner with goose or turkey, Christmas pudding, oranges, chestnuts, and punch.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Soyer set up soup kitchens in Dublin during the Great Famine of Ireland, and improved hospital catering with Florence Nightingale in the Crimean War.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Street food in Victorian England grew to include fish and chips, tripe, whelks, and pea soup.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Tea became cheap, joining white bread in the diet of the poor, who suffered widely from rickets, caused by vitamin D deficiency.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] New foods such as mangoes, pineapples, and rhubarb became available to the middle classes.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Curry arrived from British India, along with Indian restaurants.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Dickson Wright characterises the Edwardian era with the overindulged "Tum Tum", alias King Edward VII, who enjoyed sailing, horses, food, and mistresses.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] She explains Edwardian country house weekends, with soup, game pies, jellies, trifles, shooting, and bed-hopping.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Richard D'Oyly Carte staged operettas and founded the Savoy Hotel in 1889, introducing the rich to *haute cuisine*, cooked simply.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Ironically, the population was healthier than ever before, as rationing provided enough for the poorest.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Postwar, Fanny Cradock and her husband Johnnie presented cookery as television entertainment.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] After the war, many suggestions for a "perfect meal" were made, varying wildly from pizza to curry, chow mein or roast beef and Yorkshire pudding.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] The 1970s favoured prawn cocktail, cheese fondue, and Black Forest gateau; the 1990s "embraced sushi".
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Cookery writers from Elizabeth David to Delia Smith encouraged people to enjoy simple, well-cooked ingredients.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Henrietta Green championed local produce and farmers' markets.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Several reviewers broadly agreed that *A History of English Food* was informative, witty, and entertaining, though others found it unsystematic and snobbish.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] It was described by Christopher Hirst in *The Independent* as "surely destined for classic status".
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] The reviewer remarked Dickson Wright's mention of badger hams in the West Country pubs of her childhood, and the nine sorts of tripe in Dewsbury market, "including penis and udder".
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Shilling finds this "an impressive tour" from a well-stocked mind.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] She describes Dickson Wright's approach as "a firmly chronological line across the landscape of culinary history, pausing at intervals to examine objects of interest." She agrees that the book is "opinionated and wildly idiosyncratic", in the tradition of W.N.W.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Fowler's "gin-soaked" *Countryman's Cooking* and Rupert Croft-Cooke's *English Cooking: A New Approach*.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] The book gives, Shilling asserts, a "glorious" impression of English cuisine's long and continuous development since the Middle Ages.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Fay Maschler, writing in *The Spectator*, calls the book a "less stringent, more capricious, generously illustrated account", giving the reader "a magical sense of almost having been there".
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] For her, the book works because of Dickson Wright's evident enthusiasm for food and farming, especially animals.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Rachel Cooke, reviewing *A History of English Food* for *The Guardian*, writes that she feels "pretty cross.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] All of the information in this book can be found elsewhere, and much better done, too." She compares the book unfavourably with Kate Colquhoun's 2008 *Taste: The Story of Britain Through Its Cooking* and Dorothy Hartley's 1954 "classic" *Food in England*.
[src:apple-pie/a-history-of-english-food] Cooke argues that Dickson Wright is "as particular as she is greedy", and "gruesomely snobbish", out of touch with "other people", preferring therefore the overindulgent Georgians who could afford a suitable retinue of servants.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] An **apple pie** is a fruit pie in which the principal filling is apples.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] It is generally has shortcrust pastry both above and below the filling; the upper pastry may be solid or latticed (woven of crosswise strips).
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] The bottom or pastry base may be baked separately (known as "blind-baking") to prevent it from getting soggy.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Tarte Tatin is baked with the pastry on top, but this is served the opposite way round with the fruit exposed.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] First recorded in the 14th century in England, apple pie recipes are now a standard part of cuisines in many countries where apples grow.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Apple pie is a significant dessert in many countries, including the United Kingdom, Ireland, Sweden, Norway, Australia, Germany, New Zealand, and the United States.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] American apple pies are known to be considerably sweeter than their European cousins versions.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] The fruit in an apple pie can be made with many different sorts of apples.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Common cooking apples include Braeburn, Gala, Cortland, Bramley, Empire, Northern Spy, Granny Smith, and McIntosh.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] The fruit for the pie can be fresh, canned, or reconstituted from dried apples in the case of dried apple pie.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Dried or preserved apples were originally substituted only at times when fresh fruit was unavailable.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] The basic ingredients of the filling are sugar, and an acidic ingredient like lemon juice.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] A thickener like eggs or corn starch may be added, while butter is added in the US.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Spices may be added like cinnamon or nutmeg.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Lemon juice which is used to prevent oxidation of the apples when macerating the filling.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Many older recipes call for honey in place of the then-expensive sugar.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Most apple pies use shortcrust pastry, however, the tarte Tatin is traditionally made with puff pastry, while the Greek milopita bougatsa uses filo pastry.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] In the UK, custard is the traditional serving with apple pie, although cream, either whipped or poured, is also used.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Apple pie in the US is often served *à la mode*, that is, topped with ice cream.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] In another serving style originating in 17th century England, a piece of sharp cheddar or Wensleydale cheese is placed on top of a slice of the finished pie.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] This practice also occurs in the United States and Canada, particularly in regions with dairy farms, such as New England.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] A commercially prepared apple pie in the US is 52% water, 34% carbohydrates, 2% protein, and 11% fat (table).
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] A 100 g (3.5 oz) serving supplies 992 kilojoules (237 kilocalories) of food energy and 13% of the US recommended Daily Value of sodium, with no other micronutrients in significant amounts (table).
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] The 14th century recipe collection the *Forme of Cury* gives a recipe including *good apples, good spices, figs, raisins and pears* in a *cofyn*, a casing of pastry.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Lattice pastry styles were found from the 17th century alongside the more traditional dome shaped pie crust.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] In Yorkshire, *Wilfa apple cake* is served on St Wilfa's day, and although called a cake, it is made with shortcrust pastry topped with Wensleydale cheese.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] In English-speaking countries, apple pie, often considered a comfort food, is eaten hot or cold, on its own or with cream, custard or ice cream.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Apple pies are often sold in supermarkets and convenience stores as mini versions in multipacks.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Tarte aux pommes and tarte Tatin are both made with puff pastry.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] The tarte Tatin is a tart in which the apples are caramelized in butter and sugar before the tart is baked.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] The tarte is then served with the pastry served on the bottom exposing the caramelised apple.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Other variants include the Normandy tart, and Croustade.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] In Germany, the word "kuchen" encompasses desserts that English speakers may call "pie", with apple pie coming under *Apfelkuchen*.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] The traditional pastry based apple pie is known as *Gedeckter apfelkuchen* and is fully encased in pastry with the apples cooked in the oven.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Recipes for Dutch apple pie go back to the Middle Ages.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] An early Dutch language cookbook from 1514, *Een notabel boecxken van cokeryen* ("A notable little cookery book"), letterpress printed in Brussels by Thomas van der Noot, who may also have been the author, documents a recipe for *Appeltaerten* (modern Dutch *Appeltaarten* 'apple pies').
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] This early recipe was simple, requiring only shortcrust pastry, slices of especially soft apples with their skin and seeds removed, and *den selven deeghe daer die taerte af ghemaect es* (more of the same dough) on top.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] It was then baked in a typical Dutch oven.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Once baked, the top crust (except at the edges) would be cut out from the middle, after which the apple slices were potentially put through a sieve before the pie was stirred with a wooden spoon.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] At this point the book recommends adding several spices to the pie, namely: cardamom, ginger, cinnamon, nutmeg, clove, mace and powdered sugar.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Finally, after mixing the ingredients into the pie with cream, it is once again put into the oven to dry.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Traditional Dutch apple pie comes in two varieties, a crumb or streusel-top (*appelkruimeltaart*) and a lattice-top (*appeltaart*) style pie.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Both recipes are distinct in that they typically call for flavourings of cinnamon and lemon juice to be added and differ in texture, not taste.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Dutch apple pies may include ingredients such as full-cream butter, raisins and almond paste, in addition to ingredients such as apples and sugar, which they have in common with other recipes.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Both modern types have a shortcrust pastry on the bottom and around the edges.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] The apples are usually a crisp and mildly tart variety such as Goudreinet or Elstar.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] It can be eaten warm or cold, sometimes with a dash of whipped cream or vanilla ice cream.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] In Poland, *szarlotka* is regarded as apple pie.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] It has a shortcrust base, a filling of spiced shredded apple, and is either topped with more shortcrust pastry or a crumble mixture.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] There is a similar dish called *jabłecznik*, but this is considered a cake as it is not made with shortcrust pastry.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] The Swedish style apple pie, *äppelpaj* is predominantly a variety of apple crumble, rather than a traditional pastry pie.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Often, breadcrumbs are used (wholly or partially) instead of flour, and sometimes rolled oats.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] It is usually flavoured with cinnamon and served with vanilla custard or ice cream.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Apple pie was brought to the colonies by the English, the Dutch, and the Swedes during the 17th and 18th centuries.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Two recipes for apple pie appear in America's first cookbook, *American Cookery* by Amelia Simmons, which was published in 1796.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] The apple pie had to wait for the planting of European varieties, brought across the Atlantic, to become fruit-bearing apple trees, to be selected for their cooking qualities as there were no native apples except crabapples, which yield very small and sour fruit.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] In the meantime, the colonists were more likely to make their pies, or "pasties", from meat, rather than fruit; and the main use for apples, once they were available, was in cider.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] However, there are American apple pie recipes, both manuscript and printed, from the 18th century.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Apple varieties are usually propagated by grafting, as clones, but in the New World, planting from seeds was more successful, leading to development of hundreds of new native varieties.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Apple pie was a common food in 18th-century Delaware.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] As noted by the New Sweden historian Dr.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Israel Acrelius in a letter: "Apple pie is used throughout the whole year, and when fresh Apples are no longer to be had, dried ones are used.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] The mock apple pie, made from crackers, was probably invented for use aboard ships, as it was known to the British Royal Navy as early as 1812.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] The earliest known published recipes for mock apple pie date from the antebellum period of the 1850s.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] In the 1930s, and for many years afterwards, Ritz Crackers promoted a recipe for mock apple pie using its product, along with sugar and various spices.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] In the US, "Dutch apple pie" refers specifically to crumb-top variety known as appelkruimeltaart in the Netherlands.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Dried apple pie is prominent in the cuisine of the Pennsylvania Dutch, where it is known as *schnitz pie*.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Apple pie was one of the dishes that Rhode Island army officers ate for their Fourth of July celebrations during the Siege of Petersburg.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Although originating in England and eaten in Europe since long before the European colonisation of the Americas, apple pie as used in the phrase "as American as apple pie" describes something as being "typically American".
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] In the nineteenth and twentieth centuries, apple pie became a symbol of American prosperity and national pride.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] A newspaper article published in 1902 declared that "No pie-eating people can be permanently vanquished." The dish was also commemorated in the phrase "for Mom and apple pie"—supposedly the stock answer of American soldiers in World War II, whenever journalists asked why they were going to war.
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] Advertisers exploited the patriotic connection in the 1970s with the commercial jingle "baseball, hot dogs, apple pie and Chevrolet".
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] One out of five Americans surveyed (19%) prefer apple pie over all others, followed by pumpkin (13%) and pecan (12%).
[src:apple-pie/apple-pie] The unincorporated community of Pie Town, New Mexico, is named after apple pie.
